## Reaching for What You Don't Know — Form as a Movement's Signature

Forms carry lineage. Sonata-allegro is a Classical-era invention; the ABA of a Baroque aria has its own home; the AABA of a jazz standard is a movement's calling card. When you pick a form, reach for the movement whose signature it is.

### AABA and the jazz-standard lineage

You lay out an AABA. Reach for the movement to explain the shape.

```scheme
(define A '((C4 quarter 70) (E4 quarter 70) (G4 quarter 70) (C5 quarter 75)))
(define B '((F4 quarter 70) (A4 quarter 70) (C5 quarter 70) (F5 quarter 75)))

(define (play phrase) (for-each (lambda (n) (note (car n) (car (cdr n)) (car (cdr (cdr n))))) phrase))

(let ((atom (world/knowledge :movement 'swing)))
  (play A) (play A) (play B) (play A)
  (motoi/say \"AABA — the shape of a swing-era standard. Sinatra sang a thousand of these.\"))
```

Teaches: the form and the tradition are one reach apart.

### Baroque ternary form (ABA) — pointing at Baroque

A da capo aria uses ABA — an A section, a contrasting B, then a return to A (often ornamented). Reach for the Baroque atom to ground the choice.

```scheme
(define A '((D4 half 65) (F4 half 65) (A4 whole 70)))
(define B '((G4 quarter 60) (Bb4 quarter 60) (D5 half 65)))

(define (play phrase) (for-each (lambda (n) (note (car n) (car (cdr n)) (car (cdr (cdr n))))) phrase))

(let ((atom (world/knowledge :movement 'baroque-music)))
  (play A) (play B) (play A)
  (motoi/say \"ABA — the Baroque da capo form; the return is where the singer would ornament.\"))
```

Teaches: reach for the movement whose signature form you are borrowing.

